Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: National Bank Kenya, Sterling Bank

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 
2011-03-17T10:35:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-17/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-national-bank-kenya-sterling-bank.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index dropped
the most since September 2009, losing 1.6 percent to 1,946.92 by
the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped four days of gains,
retreating 0.2 percent to 74.20 by 1:02 p.m. in Nairobi. The
Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined 0.2 percent to
24,905.79 by 11:02 a.m. in Lagos, a fourth day of decreases.  Namibia ’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  was unchanged at 838.52 by
12:03 p.m. in Windhoek, while the Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index added less than 0.1 percent to 1,071.05 at 10:05 a.m. in
Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    National Bank of Kenya Ltd. (NBKL)  , a state-run lender,
fell the most in more than a week, losing 2.75 shillings, or 6.3
percent, to 41 shillings. National Bank reported net income
climbed to 2.02 billion shillings ($23.5 million) in the 12
months through December, from 1.46 billion shillings a year ago.  “The results were below our expectations,” Renaldo D’souza,
an analyst at Nairobi-based Genghis Capital Ltd., said in a
phone interview today.    Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender, snapped
two days of decreases, adding 2 kobo, or 0.8 percent to 2.45
naira. FirstRand Ltd., South Africa’s second-largest bank, is in
advanced talks to make an investment in  Nigeria ’s Sterling Bank,
Reuters said, citing people in the banking industry it didn’t
identify. FirstRand is looking to enter the Nigerian market
through a strategic alliance with a healthy local bank and spend
as much as $400 million to fund such an investment, the news
service said, citing the people.  To contact the reporters on this story:
